1
00:00:41,876 --> 00:00:44,948
An unidentified radio source
from deep space...

2
00:00:45,196 --> 00:00:47,152
...can neither be confirmed nor denied.

3
00:00:47,516 --> 00:00:49,154
Whatever it is, it ain't local.

4
00:00:49,396 --> 00:00:50,385
Position?

5
00:00:50,636 --> 00:00:52,228
Only 26 light years away.

6
00:00:52,476 --> 00:00:53,955
Sending this all over the world...

7
00:00:54,196 --> 00:00:55,948
...may be a national security breach.

8
00:00:56,436 --> 00:00:57,710
lt isn't a person-to-person call.

9
00:00:57,956 --> 00:01:00,026
lt's an announcement to get our
attention.

10
00:01:00,276 --> 00:01:01,789
The President's called a meeting.

11
00:01:02,036 --> 00:01:04,106
We must militarize this project.

12
00:01:04,356 --> 00:01:07,029
There's no reason to believe
their intentions are hostile.

13
00:01:07,276 --> 00:01:08,152
There's no proof of that.

14
00:01:08,396 --> 00:01:09,351
They don't speak English?

15
00:01:09,596 --> 00:01:12,508
We believe the message
contains instructions...

16
00:01:12,796 --> 00:01:15,310
...to build some kind of transport.

17
00:01:16,596 --> 00:01:18,507
You don't know what it does.

18
00:01:18,756 --> 00:01:20,428
No one says it's not dangerous.

19
00:01:20,676 --> 00:01:22,746
-They'll build it.
-Who gets to go?

20
00:01:23,036 --> 00:01:26,472
You're willing to risk your life
and die for this.

21
00:01:26,716 --> 00:01:28,149
Why?

22
00:02:37,246 --> 00:02:40,283
An unidentified radio source
from deep space...

23
00:02:40,526 --> 00:02:42,756
...can neither be confirmed nor denied.

24
00:02:43,006 --> 00:02:44,644
Whatever it is, it ain't local.

25
00:02:44,886 --> 00:02:45,523
Position?

26
00:02:45,766 --> 00:02:48,326
l checked interferometry.
ln Lyra, l think.

27
00:02:48,606 --> 00:02:49,755
-Vega?
-No!

28
00:02:50,006 --> 00:02:51,997
lt's only 26 light years away.

29
00:02:52,286 --> 00:02:53,844
l want all these people out of here.

30
00:02:54,086 --> 00:02:55,314
Sending this all over the world...

31
00:02:55,566 --> 00:02:57,238
...may be a national security breach.

32
00:02:57,686 --> 00:02:59,085
lt's not person-to-person.

33
00:02:59,326 --> 00:03:01,362
This may be an announcement
to get our attention.

34
00:03:01,646 --> 00:03:02,840
The President's called a meeting.

35
00:03:03,126 --> 00:03:05,640
Those frames we thought were noise?
This has structure.

36
00:03:05,886 --> 00:03:08,116
l recommend we militarize this project.

37
00:03:08,366 --> 00:03:11,119
No reason to believe
their intentions are hostile.

38
00:03:11,366 --> 00:03:12,116
There's no proof.

39
00:03:12,446 --> 00:03:13,356
They don't speak English?

40
00:03:13,606 --> 00:03:15,722
Mathematics is the only
universal language.

41
00:03:16,086 --> 00:03:17,917
Buried within the message...

42
00:03:18,166 --> 00:03:19,758
...is the key to decoding it.

43
00:03:20,326 --> 00:03:22,521
Those look like blueprints.

44
00:03:22,766 --> 00:03:25,519
We believe the message
contains instructions...

45
00:03:25,766 --> 00:03:27,836
...for building some kind of machine.

46
00:03:28,886 --> 00:03:32,083
lt might turn out to be
some kind of a transport.

47
00:03:33,486 --> 00:03:35,636
You don't know what it does.
lt could be anything.

48
00:03:35,926 --> 00:03:37,996
-Nobody's saying this isn't dangerous.
-They're going to build it.

49
00:03:38,246 --> 00:03:39,042
Who goes?

50
00:03:39,286 --> 00:03:40,799
-lt's complicated.
-Who?

51
00:03:42,166 --> 00:03:43,997
You're willing to risk your life...

52
00:03:44,246 --> 00:03:45,565
...and die for this.

53
00:03:45,806 --> 00:03:47,285
Why?

54
00:05:08,277 --> 00:05:11,155
<i>It's obviously a major malfunction.</i>

55
00:05:26,677 --> 00:05:29,191
<i>...their President is a crook.</i>
<i>Well, I'm not a crook.</i>

56
00:05:32,797 --> 00:05:36,312
<i>Robert Kennedy was shot</i>
<i>in that ballroom.</i>

57
00:05:38,637 --> 00:05:40,912
<i>Thank God Almighty,</i>
<i>we are free at last!</i>

58
00:05:41,117 --> 00:05:43,790
<i>A sniper has fired</i>
<i>at President Kennedy.</i>

59
00:05:50,797 --> 00:05:54,631
<i>Or have you ever been</i>
<i>a member of the Communist party?</i>

60
00:05:58,637 --> 00:06:00,548
<i>Hi</i>-<i>yo, Silver!</i>

61
00:06:05,077 --> 00:06:06,635
<i>... 194 1...</i>

62
00:06:07,197 --> 00:06:10,234
<i>...a date which will live in infamy.</i>

63
00:06:14,157 --> 00:06:18,150
<i>We bring you the final edition of</i>
<i>our Maxwell House Good News of 1939.</i>

64
00:06:18,517 --> 00:06:21,748
<i>Good evening, Mr. and Mrs. North</i>
<i>America, and all the ships at sea.</i>

65
00:06:26,477 --> 00:06:30,470
<i>The only thing we have to fear</i>
<i>is fear itself.</i>

66
00:07:37,237 --> 00:07:38,306
<i>CQ...</i>

67
00:07:38,717 --> 00:07:40,628
<i>...this is W</i>-<i>9 GFO.</i>

68
00:07:42,837 --> 00:07:45,988
CQ, this is W-9 GFO here.
Come back?

69
00:07:49,837 --> 00:07:50,952
CQ...

70
00:07:51,157 --> 00:07:53,671
...this is W-9 GFO here.

71
00:07:54,517 --> 00:07:55,666
Come back?

72
00:07:59,437 --> 00:08:03,430
CQ, this is W-9 GFO.
ls anybody out there?

73
00:08:04,397 --> 00:08:05,466
Not getting anything.

74
00:08:05,757 --> 00:08:07,190
Small moves, Ellie.

75
00:08:08,837 --> 00:08:09,906
Small moves.

76
00:08:12,437 --> 00:08:15,986
CQ, this is W-9 GFO here.
Come back?

77
00:08:16,917 --> 00:08:18,509
<i>Copy, W</i>-<i>9 GFO.</i>

78
00:08:18,677 --> 00:08:20,474
<i>K</i>-<i>4 WLD here.</i>

79
00:08:20,917 --> 00:08:22,270
What do l say?

80
00:08:22,437 --> 00:08:23,870
Just be yourself.

81
00:08:24,317 --> 00:08:26,877
Where are you, K-4 WLD?
Come back?

82
00:08:27,117 --> 00:08:28,345
<i>Pensacola.</i>
<i>Over.</i>

83
00:08:28,597 --> 00:08:30,076
Pensacola, where's Pensacola?

84
00:08:30,437 --> 00:08:31,836
l'll give you a hint.

85
00:08:32,477 --> 00:08:33,546
Orange juice.

86
00:08:36,277 --> 00:08:39,792
Copy that, K-4 WLD. How's the
weather down there in Florida?

87
00:08:40,957 --> 00:08:42,834
Pensacola, Florida.

88
00:08:43,517 --> 00:08:45,314
l have to tell you, Sparks.

89
00:08:46,077 --> 00:08:48,307
1,116 miles.

90
00:08:49,757 --> 00:08:50,872
Pretty good.

91
00:08:51,197 --> 00:08:52,596
That's the farthest yet.

92
00:09:04,957 --> 00:09:06,709
Can we hear all the way to New York?

93
00:09:06,997 --> 00:09:08,112
Sure.

94
00:09:09,437 --> 00:09:11,348
Can we hear all the way
to California?

95
00:09:11,637 --> 00:09:13,275
l don't see why not.

96
00:09:13,957 --> 00:09:15,868
Can we hear all the way to Alaska?

97
00:09:16,277 --> 00:09:17,505
On a really clear day.

98
00:09:17,717 --> 00:09:19,628
Can we hear all the way to China?

99
00:09:20,637 --> 00:09:23,026
On a really, really clear day.

100
00:09:24,797 --> 00:09:26,867
Could we talk to the moon?

101
00:09:27,517 --> 00:09:30,190
lf it's a big enough radio,
l don't see why not.

102
00:09:30,837 --> 00:09:32,748
Could we talk to Jupiter?

103
00:09:32,957 --> 00:09:35,346
Or what's the one after that?

104
00:09:35,797 --> 00:09:37,116
Don't tell me.

105
00:09:39,357 --> 00:09:40,676
l'll give you a hint.

106
00:09:41,117 --> 00:09:42,186
Hula-Hoops.

107
00:09:42,397 --> 00:09:44,308
Saturn!
Could we talk to Saturn?

108
00:09:49,757 --> 00:09:52,146
Dad, could we talk to Mom?

109
00:09:57,597 --> 00:10:00,669
l don't think even the biggest radio
could reach that far.

110
00:10:05,477 --> 00:10:07,229
All right, no more stalling.

111
00:10:11,997 --> 00:10:13,396
Pensacola!

112
00:10:20,917 --> 00:10:22,111
That's a beauty.

113
00:10:23,517 --> 00:10:24,916
Now get some sleep.

114
00:10:32,957 --> 00:10:34,185
Hey, Dad?

115
00:10:35,197 --> 00:10:37,757
Do you think there's people
on other planets?

116
00:10:37,917 --> 00:10:39,555
l don't know, Sparks.

117
00:10:40,957 --> 00:10:42,549
But l guess l'd say...

118
00:10:43,037 --> 00:10:44,789
...if it is just us...

119
00:10:46,397 --> 00:10:48,467
...it seems like
an awful waste of space.

120
00:11:07,357 --> 00:11:09,587
CQ, this is W-9 GFO.

121
00:11:09,757 --> 00:11:12,317
Repeat. This is W-9 GFO.
Come back?

122
00:11:19,997 --> 00:11:21,908
l'm going to need a bigger antenna.

123
00:11:47,837 --> 00:11:49,395
What do you think, Doc Arroway?

124
00:11:49,637 --> 00:11:51,036
lsn't she a beauty?

125
00:11:54,997 --> 00:11:56,066
lt'll do.

126
00:11:56,317 --> 00:11:58,194
The village is five miles away.

127
00:11:58,557 --> 00:12:00,513
There's a general store
in the cantina.

128
00:12:00,677 --> 00:12:02,713
They can order anything
from San Juan.

129
00:12:02,877 --> 00:12:04,310
When can l get dish time?

130
00:12:04,477 --> 00:12:07,992
Dr. Clark said you couldn't wait.
Your first shift is tonight.

131
00:13:01,757 --> 00:13:02,872
Go back.

132
00:13:04,757 --> 00:13:07,396
Try back a little bit.
You had something there.

133
00:13:08,637 --> 00:13:09,592
There!

134
00:13:09,917 --> 00:13:12,989
-Right there?
-You hear it? Right there, that's it.

135
00:13:13,277 --> 00:13:16,792
All right, 1221 .46.
That's well within the L-band.

136
00:13:17,117 --> 00:13:18,072
Check off-axis.

137
00:13:19,037 --> 00:13:20,072
On it.

138
00:13:21,957 --> 00:13:23,356
lt's not in the neighborhood.

139
00:13:31,837 --> 00:13:33,748
Here it is.
J-1741 ...

140
00:13:34,037 --> 00:13:35,629
... + 2748.

141
00:13:35,837 --> 00:13:38,874
Catalogued November 4, 1982.
Pulsar.

142
00:13:41,437 --> 00:13:44,429
Must've been the glitch
in the timing that threw me.

143
00:13:44,637 --> 00:13:46,229
Must've been a starquake.

144
00:13:47,517 --> 00:13:51,351
l think it's great that you listen.
Most don't do that anymore.

145
00:13:51,517 --> 00:13:54,190
lt's just an old habit.
lt makes it feel more real.

146
00:13:54,397 --> 00:13:55,273
Ellie.

147
00:13:55,517 --> 00:13:56,632
Kent Clark.

148
00:13:59,397 --> 00:14:00,910
They said you'd been...

149
00:14:01,117 --> 00:14:03,426
...up at Owen's Valley
working under Drumlin.

150
00:14:03,637 --> 00:14:04,956
How'd you like him?

151
00:14:08,037 --> 00:14:11,996
That much? About what l'd expect
after what he had to say about you.

152
00:14:12,317 --> 00:14:13,909
And what was that?

153
00:14:14,397 --> 00:14:15,830
That you are brilliant...

154
00:14:16,117 --> 00:14:17,266
...driven...

155
00:14:17,597 --> 00:14:19,030
...a major pain in the ass...

156
00:14:19,317 --> 00:14:22,070
...and obsessed with a field
of study he considers tantamount...

157
00:14:22,237 --> 00:14:23,636
...to professional suicide.

158
00:14:24,357 --> 00:14:25,312
Anything else?

159
00:14:25,477 --> 00:14:27,195
Those were the highlights.

160
00:14:27,637 --> 00:14:30,071
David, Dr. Vernon.
Dr. Arroway.

161
00:14:31,477 --> 00:14:35,516
Believe you've already met our tireless
research assistant, Mr. Fisher...

162
00:14:36,157 --> 00:14:38,387
...as well as his cologne.

163
00:14:38,997 --> 00:14:41,272
Brook's looking at the black hole
in M-87.

164
00:14:41,437 --> 00:14:45,112
Ellie's studying Markarian 541,
a major gamma ray source.

165
00:14:45,437 --> 00:14:49,874
Dr. Arroway will be spending her
precious telescope time listening for...

166
00:14:50,597 --> 00:14:52,474
...listening for...

167
00:14:52,677 --> 00:14:54,110
Little green men.

168
00:15:01,877 --> 00:15:03,105
One down...

169
00:15:03,677 --> 00:15:05,235
...a couple billion to go.

170
00:15:21,357 --> 00:15:23,109
Arecibo, right?

171
00:15:24,277 --> 00:15:25,392
Does it show?

172
00:15:27,437 --> 00:15:28,506
Cracker Jack?

173
00:15:28,757 --> 00:15:29,473
No, thanks.

174
00:15:29,717 --> 00:15:30,945
Mind if l sit down?

175
00:15:32,797 --> 00:15:36,551
l hear the locals,
they call it "El Radar."

176
00:15:36,757 --> 00:15:39,271
Convinced it has some
dark military purpose.

177
00:15:39,677 --> 00:15:40,996
l think we're harmless.

178
00:15:42,437 --> 00:15:43,506
Palmer Joss.

179
00:15:44,317 --> 00:15:46,672
-Ellie Arroway.
-Nice to meet you, Ellie.

180
00:15:47,877 --> 00:15:50,516
What are you studying up there?

181
00:15:52,277 --> 00:15:53,596
The usual.

182
00:15:53,757 --> 00:15:57,432
Nebulae, quasars, pulsars,
stuff like that.

183
00:15:57,757 --> 00:15:59,190
What are you writing?

184
00:15:59,517 --> 00:16:01,553
The usual.
Nouns, adverbs...

185
00:16:01,797 --> 00:16:03,276
...adjective here and there.

186
00:16:04,957 --> 00:16:06,390
l work on a project, SETl.

187
00:16:07,197 --> 00:16:09,108
Search for
Extraterrestrial lntelligence?

188
00:16:11,197 --> 00:16:12,835
That is out there!

189
00:16:13,957 --> 00:16:16,187
Are you a student or something?

190
00:16:16,677 --> 00:16:18,713
l'm a writer.
l'm writing a book.

191
00:16:19,197 --> 00:16:20,471
l'm here doing research...

192
00:16:20,637 --> 00:16:23,674
...about how technology affects
Third World cultures.

193
00:16:23,837 --> 00:16:26,397
l'm also looking for this guy,
David Drumlin.

194
00:16:26,677 --> 00:16:30,590
He's head of the National Science
Foundation. l want an interview.

195
00:16:31,837 --> 00:16:33,475
l take it you know him?

196
00:16:34,917 --> 00:16:36,316
You could say that.

197
00:16:37,597 --> 00:16:38,996
SETl.

198
00:16:39,197 --> 00:16:40,789
That's fringe!

199
00:16:41,237 --> 00:16:45,469
l've crossed paths with him. Something
like that must really chap his ass.

200
00:16:48,317 --> 00:16:49,306
Compass.

201
00:16:51,237 --> 00:16:52,465
That's for you.

202
00:16:57,117 --> 00:16:58,516
You better keep this.

203
00:16:59,677 --> 00:17:01,269
Might save your life someday.

204
00:17:05,877 --> 00:17:07,390
Have dinner with me tonight?

205
00:17:10,237 --> 00:17:13,434
l don't make a good
research subject. l'm not quotable.

206
00:17:13,717 --> 00:17:15,947
No quotes.
Scout's honor.

207
00:17:16,317 --> 00:17:17,591
Good meal, good company.

208
00:17:18,397 --> 00:17:19,671
l've got to go.

209
00:17:28,437 --> 00:17:30,189
Drumlin's coming in Tuesday.

210
00:17:38,717 --> 00:17:41,914
Now l remember
why l took that desk job.

211
00:17:43,397 --> 00:17:45,308
Dr. Drumlin, how are you?

212
00:17:46,877 --> 00:17:48,310
Glad you could make it.

213
00:17:49,437 --> 00:17:52,270
lf l'd known it took 3 planes,
l might've reconsidered.

214
00:17:52,477 --> 00:17:53,751
How is that new office?

215
00:17:53,957 --> 00:17:58,473
Still settling in. They already want to
give half my budget to the Pentagon.

216
00:17:59,197 --> 00:18:01,427
Still waiting for E.T. to call?

217
00:18:03,357 --> 00:18:04,949
Good to see you too!

218
00:18:05,437 --> 00:18:06,392
Asshole!

219
00:18:06,677 --> 00:18:08,747
Looks like it's
going to be a long night.

220
00:18:08,997 --> 00:18:13,434
Science must be accountable to the
people paying for it, the taxpayers.

221
00:18:13,597 --> 00:18:16,794
We must stop wasting money
on pie-in-the-sky abstractions...

222
00:18:16,957 --> 00:18:19,676
...and spend it on practical,
measurable ways...

223
00:18:19,837 --> 00:18:22,431
...to improve the lives
of the people who are paying.

224
00:18:22,597 --> 00:18:25,634
Not unlike my L-band,
globular clusters work.

225
00:18:25,877 --> 00:18:28,710
You want to do away
with all pure research now?

226
00:18:28,917 --> 00:18:32,148
What's wrong with science
being practical? Even profitable?

227
00:18:32,357 --> 00:18:34,393
Nothing, as long as your motive...

228
00:18:34,677 --> 00:18:38,386
...is the search for truth. Which is
what the pursuit of science is.

229
00:18:40,917 --> 00:18:43,192
That's an interesting position
from a man...

230
00:18:43,397 --> 00:18:45,911
...on a crusade against
the evils of technology...

231
00:18:46,197 --> 00:18:47,312
...Father Joss.

232
00:18:47,957 --> 00:18:51,154
l'm not against technology, Doctor.
l'm against...

233
00:18:51,357 --> 00:18:54,429
...the men who deify it
at the expense of human truth.

234
00:18:58,357 --> 00:19:01,588
Kent, l need to have
a word with you. Over here, please.

235
00:19:07,037 --> 00:19:10,029
You think that hurt my chances
with that interview?

236
00:19:10,637 --> 00:19:11,990
You're a priest?

237
00:19:13,837 --> 00:19:14,952
Not really.

238
00:19:15,677 --> 00:19:18,316
l got my Masters in Divinity...

239
00:19:18,797 --> 00:19:22,073
...then left the seminary to do
secular humanitarian work...

240
00:19:22,317 --> 00:19:24,626
...coordinating
Third World churches.

241
00:19:25,357 --> 00:19:27,348
l couldn't live
with the celibacy thing.

242
00:19:31,757 --> 00:19:33,748
You could call me
a man of the cloth...

243
00:19:34,957 --> 00:19:36,470
...without the cloth.

244
00:19:39,677 --> 00:19:41,235
You want to get out of here?

245
00:19:43,157 --> 00:19:47,787
You see that large W-shaped
constellation there? That's Cassiopeia.

246
00:19:48,157 --> 00:19:52,389
And Cassiopeia A gives off
a whole lot of radio signals.

247
00:19:52,757 --> 00:19:54,315
l listen to them a lot.

248
00:19:54,597 --> 00:19:56,792
lt's a remnant of a supernova.

249
00:19:57,717 --> 00:20:00,277
When did you know
you wanted to be an astronomer?

250
00:20:02,517 --> 00:20:04,667
When l was about eight years old...

251
00:20:04,957 --> 00:20:06,549
...watching the sunset...

252
00:20:07,557 --> 00:20:09,593
...l asked Dad, "What's that bright
star over there?"

253
00:20:12,957 --> 00:20:15,915
<i>He said that it wasn't a star.</i>
<i>It was...</i>

254
00:20:17,757 --> 00:20:20,066
<i>...a whole planet called Venus...</i>

255
00:20:23,517 --> 00:20:26,634
...which should be over there soon.

256
00:20:27,597 --> 00:20:29,872
He said,
"You know why they called it Venus?

257
00:20:30,317 --> 00:20:33,434
Because they thought
it was so beautiful and glowing.

258
00:20:33,677 --> 00:20:35,190
But they didn't know...

259
00:20:35,877 --> 00:20:38,345
...that it's filled with...

260
00:20:39,517 --> 00:20:42,793
...deadly gases
and sulfuric acid rain."

261
00:20:44,077 --> 00:20:47,467
Wow, l thought,
"This is it! l'm hooked!"

262
00:20:49,597 --> 00:20:53,146
There are four hundred billion
stars out there...

263
00:20:53,357 --> 00:20:55,154
...just in our galaxy alone.

264
00:20:56,117 --> 00:20:59,587
lf only one out of a million
of those had planets...

265
00:20:59,997 --> 00:21:02,955
...if just one out of a million
of those had life...

266
00:21:03,157 --> 00:21:07,150
...and if just one out of a million
of those had intelligent life...

267
00:21:07,917 --> 00:21:12,274
...there would be literally millions
of civilizations out there.

268
00:21:14,077 --> 00:21:15,590
lf there wasn't...

269
00:21:16,477 --> 00:21:18,547
...it'd be an awful waste of space.

270
00:21:24,237 --> 00:21:25,352
Amen.

271
00:21:33,917 --> 00:21:37,751
So l was lying there,
just looking at the sky.

272
00:21:41,517 --> 00:21:44,395
And then l felt something.
l don't know.

273
00:21:45,677 --> 00:21:48,237
All l know is that l wasn't alone.

274
00:21:48,597 --> 00:21:52,670
For the first time in my life
l wasn't scared of nothing...

275
00:21:53,557 --> 00:21:55,070
...not even dying.

276
00:22:00,477 --> 00:22:02,274
lt was God.

277
00:22:04,797 --> 00:22:06,708
And there's no chance that...

278
00:22:07,197 --> 00:22:11,270
...you had this experience because
some part of you needed to have it?

279
00:22:12,477 --> 00:22:15,833
l'm a reasonably intelligent guy,
but this...

280
00:22:18,597 --> 00:22:22,067
My intellect
couldn't even touch this.

281
00:22:22,557 --> 00:22:23,512
No.

282
00:22:25,917 --> 00:22:28,385
l've been to Sunday school
a few times.

283
00:22:30,557 --> 00:22:31,387
And?

284
00:22:31,597 --> 00:22:35,954
l kept asking all these
really annoying questions like...

285
00:22:36,837 --> 00:22:39,192
..."Where did Mrs. Cain come from?"

286
00:22:41,037 --> 00:22:43,232
And pretty soon they asked my dad...

287
00:22:43,477 --> 00:22:46,071
...if he wouldn't mind
keeping me home from now on.

288
00:22:46,357 --> 00:22:47,585
Your dad...

289
00:22:49,237 --> 00:22:50,716
ls it this guy?

290
00:22:50,877 --> 00:22:52,026
Yeah.

291
00:22:54,117 --> 00:22:56,028
You're close to him, aren't you?

292
00:22:57,277 --> 00:23:00,235
l was. He died
when l was nine years old.

293
00:23:02,397 --> 00:23:04,308
l never got to know my mother.

294
00:23:05,837 --> 00:23:07,111
l'm sorry.

295
00:23:11,477 --> 00:23:13,308
That's got to be tough.

296
00:23:17,597 --> 00:23:19,189
Being alone.

297
00:23:27,717 --> 00:23:28,866
What do you say...

298
00:23:29,077 --> 00:23:32,467
...we pack a picnic tomorrow
and hike up to Mount Arecibo?

299
00:23:33,277 --> 00:23:36,155
l don't think l can.
l've got to work.

300
00:23:37,877 --> 00:23:41,153
How about dinner tomorrow night?
l know a great dive.

301
00:23:41,517 --> 00:23:43,075
No, l don't think so.

302
00:23:47,517 --> 00:23:49,553
Ellie, did l miss something?

303
00:23:51,677 --> 00:23:52,746
No.

304
00:23:52,957 --> 00:23:54,709
Shit, l'm late!

305
00:23:55,677 --> 00:23:58,430
l told Kent
that l'd be there at 10:30.

306
00:24:00,957 --> 00:24:02,675
l'm not trying to push you.

307
00:24:02,877 --> 00:24:05,072
l've wanted to look at
this sector for weeks.

308
00:24:05,277 --> 00:24:06,869
Just hang out...

309
00:24:07,197 --> 00:24:10,075
...and sleep in.
There's food in the fridge.

310
00:24:11,677 --> 00:24:12,746
How can l reach you?

311
00:24:14,237 --> 00:24:16,467
Just leave your number.
l'll call you.

312
00:24:37,317 --> 00:24:38,227
<i>Dad!</i>

313
00:24:40,197 --> 00:24:42,711
lt's starting,
you're going to miss it!

314
00:24:46,077 --> 00:24:48,193
Dad, there's another one!
Hurry up!

315
00:24:48,437 --> 00:24:50,632
ln a minute, Sparks!
l'm almost done.

316
00:24:50,877 --> 00:24:53,266
There's another one.
Come on, hurry up, Dad!

317
00:25:46,637 --> 00:25:47,786
l'll get the medicine.

318
00:27:04,237 --> 00:27:06,876
l know it's hard
to understand this now...

319
00:27:07,757 --> 00:27:12,069
...but we aren't always meant to know
why things happen the way they do.

320
00:27:12,597 --> 00:27:14,792
Sometimes,
we just have to accept it...

321
00:27:14,997 --> 00:27:16,749
...as God's will.

322
00:27:18,637 --> 00:27:21,674
l should have kept medicine
in the downstairs bathroom.

323
00:27:22,317 --> 00:27:24,467
Then l could've gotten to it sooner.

324
00:27:49,237 --> 00:27:50,511
<i>CQ...</i>

325
00:27:51,677 --> 00:27:54,589
<i>...this is W</i>-<i>9 GFO.</i>
<i>Do you copy?</i>

326
00:27:57,997 --> 00:28:00,192
Dad, this is Ellie.
Come back.

327
00:28:03,437 --> 00:28:05,314
This is Eleanor Arroway...

328
00:28:05,557 --> 00:28:08,435
...transmitting on 14.2 megahertz.

329
00:28:14,877 --> 00:28:16,310
Are you there?

330
00:28:18,357 --> 00:28:19,710
Come back.

331
00:28:26,237 --> 00:28:27,556
Are you there?

332
00:28:28,597 --> 00:28:30,394
<i>Dad, this is Ellie.</i>

333
00:29:01,637 --> 00:29:04,390
Hi, Kent.
What are you doing up so early?

334
00:29:05,557 --> 00:29:06,785
l was thinking...

335
00:29:07,677 --> 00:29:09,588
...we'd make a pretty good team.

336
00:29:10,197 --> 00:29:13,587
We could put together
an ad hoc SETl program.

337
00:29:13,797 --> 00:29:16,027
You know the Very Large Array
in New Mexico?

338
00:29:16,317 --> 00:29:18,433
lt's a dynamite place
to do SETl work...

339
00:29:18,677 --> 00:29:20,349
What are you talking about?

340
00:29:22,717 --> 00:29:24,389
Drumlin pulled the plug.

341
00:29:25,117 --> 00:29:26,072
We're homeless.

342
00:29:39,797 --> 00:29:41,355
lt's true, you pulled the plug?

343
00:29:41,557 --> 00:29:44,025
You can't see it now,
but l'm doing you a favor.

344
00:29:44,197 --> 00:29:48,031
You're too promising a scientist to
waste your gifts on this nonsense.

345
00:29:48,237 --> 00:29:50,148
l don't consider what could be...

346
00:29:50,357 --> 00:29:53,076
...the most important
human discovery nonsense!

347
00:29:53,397 --> 00:29:54,716
400 billion stars...

348
00:29:54,877 --> 00:29:57,675
And two probabilities.
One, there's intelligent life...

349
00:29:57,877 --> 00:30:00,266
...but too far away
to contact in your lifetime.

350
00:30:00,917 --> 00:30:02,748
-And two!
-You're making a decision...

351
00:30:03,237 --> 00:30:06,149
There's nothing but gases
and carbon compounds...

352
00:30:06,357 --> 00:30:07,346
...and you're wasting your time!

353
00:30:07,637 --> 00:30:10,470
ln the meantime,
you won't be taken seriously.

354
00:30:10,677 --> 00:30:12,269
Your career will be over!

355
00:30:12,477 --> 00:30:13,592
So what?

356
00:30:13,917 --> 00:30:15,316
lt's my life!

357
00:30:51,437 --> 00:30:53,826
Hey, Kent.
You were right.

358
00:30:54,237 --> 00:30:57,752
Screw Drumlin. We'll raise the money
ourselves. We'll go to New Mexico.

359
00:30:58,077 --> 00:31:00,227
Chicago's set.
Let me know how it goes.

360
00:31:00,437 --> 00:31:03,235
l've got more corporate stops
on the East Coast for you.

361
00:31:03,437 --> 00:31:06,429
Did that investor from Houston
ever get back to us?

362
00:31:06,677 --> 00:31:08,588
l'll hit him up on my way to L.A.

363
00:31:08,757 --> 00:31:10,793
Beg for some of that
Hollywood money!

364
00:31:10,997 --> 00:31:13,955
They've been making
money off aliens for years.

365
00:31:14,557 --> 00:31:17,151
-Begging is good for the soul.
-We'll see.

366
00:31:17,437 --> 00:31:19,075
Just do me a favor.

367
00:31:19,357 --> 00:31:21,746
Try not to be too...confrontational.

368
00:31:22,197 --> 00:31:24,427
Confrontational? Me?
What do you mean?

369
00:31:24,637 --> 00:31:26,229
l'll see if l left anything.

370
00:31:58,157 --> 00:32:01,786
<i>It's a unique time in our history,</i>
<i>in the history of any civilization.</i>

371
00:32:01,997 --> 00:32:04,636
<i>It's the moment</i>
<i>of the acquisition of technology.</i>

372
00:32:04,837 --> 00:32:07,590
<i>That's the moment</i>
<i>where contact becomes possible.</i>

373
00:32:08,317 --> 00:32:10,547
The Very Large Array
in New Mexico...

374
00:32:10,717 --> 00:32:12,912
...is the key to our chances
for success.

375
00:32:13,077 --> 00:32:15,113
With its 27
linked radio telescopes...

376
00:32:15,317 --> 00:32:18,707
...we can search more accurately
than at any other facility.

377
00:32:18,917 --> 00:32:23,433
We've gotten approval to buy the
telescope time from the government.

378
00:32:24,277 --> 00:32:26,393
Now all we really need is the money.

379
00:32:27,037 --> 00:32:28,948
A nice presentation, Doctor.

380
00:32:29,637 --> 00:32:32,515
But while our foundation arm
has a mandate to support...

381
00:32:32,717 --> 00:32:35,709
...experimental programs,
your proposal...

382
00:32:35,957 --> 00:32:39,791
...seems less like science,
and more like science fiction.

383
00:32:42,157 --> 00:32:43,556
Science fiction.

384
00:32:46,837 --> 00:32:48,156
You're right.

385
00:32:48,957 --> 00:32:50,276
lt's crazy.

386
00:32:51,317 --> 00:32:53,751
ln fact, it's even worse
than that: nuts!

387
00:32:55,757 --> 00:32:57,156
Want to hear something nutty?

388
00:32:57,357 --> 00:32:59,791
Two guys wanted to build
a thing called an airplane.

389
00:32:59,997 --> 00:33:02,909
People go in it and fly like birds.
Ridiculous, right?

390
00:33:03,117 --> 00:33:04,835
What about breaking
the sound barrier...

391
00:33:05,037 --> 00:33:08,632
...or rockets to the moon, or atomic
energy or a mission to Mars?

392
00:33:08,797 --> 00:33:10,435
Science fiction, right?

393
00:33:12,077 --> 00:33:16,116
All l'm asking is for you to
just have the tiniest bit of vision.

394
00:33:16,397 --> 00:33:19,594
To step back
and look at the big picture.

395
00:33:19,997 --> 00:33:24,832
Take a chance on something which could
end up the most impactful moment...

396
00:33:25,037 --> 00:33:27,267
...for humanity, for the history...

397
00:33:27,837 --> 00:33:29,111
...of history.

398
00:33:32,717 --> 00:33:33,672
l'm sorry.

399
00:33:34,717 --> 00:33:36,309
l just spent 13 months...

400
00:33:36,877 --> 00:33:39,596
...coming into rooms
and talking to people like you.

401
00:33:40,477 --> 00:33:41,751
You're my last chance.

402
00:33:43,197 --> 00:33:44,676
Sorry l wasted your time.

403
00:33:44,917 --> 00:33:45,429
Doctor.

404
00:33:46,277 --> 00:33:47,312
Yes, sir.

405
00:33:59,197 --> 00:34:00,391
You have your money.

406
00:34:03,317 --> 00:34:04,386
Thank you.

407
00:34:06,397 --> 00:34:07,352
Thank you.

408
00:34:53,397 --> 00:34:56,275
Perfect cast!
Come on, fishy!

409
00:34:56,517 --> 00:34:57,996
Frank, look at the size...

410
00:34:58,157 --> 00:35:00,068
...of that son of a bitch!

411
00:35:11,997 --> 00:35:13,874
Welcome back, Dr. C.

412
00:35:14,117 --> 00:35:15,550
How'd it go?

413
00:35:16,237 --> 00:35:17,716
How was the trip?

414
00:35:17,917 --> 00:35:19,350
l've had better.

415
00:35:19,957 --> 00:35:22,869
Drumlin!
ls this a personal vendetta now?

416
00:35:23,077 --> 00:35:26,786
There's been enormous pressure
from other scientists as well.

417
00:35:26,957 --> 00:35:29,949
lt doesn't matter. Hadden's funding
us for 2 more years.

418
00:35:30,157 --> 00:35:34,514
The government doesn't want their
telescopes used by the high priestess...

419
00:35:34,677 --> 00:35:36,588
...of the desert anymore.

420
00:35:37,877 --> 00:35:38,787
What?

421
00:35:38,957 --> 00:35:42,188
Staring at TV static for hours,
listening to washing machines.

422
00:35:42,397 --> 00:35:44,308
These stories get out!

423
00:35:44,517 --> 00:35:46,075
l was seeking patterns in the chaos!

424
00:35:46,277 --> 00:35:48,313
lt doesn't matter,
we're a joke to them.

425
00:35:48,477 --> 00:35:49,796
They want us out!

426
00:35:51,517 --> 00:35:54,270
We've got 3 months
till the paperwork goes through.

427
00:35:57,957 --> 00:36:00,027
l'll start looking for
other funding.

428
00:36:00,557 --> 00:36:04,186
Could you face reality?
Just this once? We lost.

429
00:36:04,837 --> 00:36:06,156
lt's over.

430
00:36:12,517 --> 00:36:13,632
Fine.

431
00:36:14,277 --> 00:36:15,835
l'm not stopping.

432
00:36:16,357 --> 00:36:19,349
lf l have to, l'll go it alone.
l've done it before.

433
00:37:06,997 --> 00:37:10,546
<i>My guest tonight is author</i>
<i>and theologian Palmer Joss.</i>

434
00:37:11,117 --> 00:37:13,870
<i>He's become a spiritual counselor...</i>

435
00:37:14,037 --> 00:37:15,390
<i>...and a recent fixture</i>
<i>at the White House.</i>

436
00:37:15,677 --> 00:37:18,555
<i>"God's Diplomat, "</i>
<i>according to The New York Times.</i>

437
00:37:18,717 --> 00:37:22,232
<i>His latest book, "Losing Faith, "</i>
<i>is currently number one...</i>

438
00:37:22,437 --> 00:37:24,632
<i>...on that publication's</i>
<i>bestseller list.</i>

439
00:37:24,877 --> 00:37:27,710
<i>Thanks for being here.</i>
<i>You've had quite a ride...</i>

440
00:37:27,877 --> 00:37:29,276
<i>...the last few years.</i>

441
00:37:29,477 --> 00:37:31,069
<i>Yeah, I sure have, Larry.</i>

442
00:37:31,837 --> 00:37:33,953
Fish, l was thinking.

443
00:37:34,437 --> 00:37:38,555
Who would make the best astronomers?
Think about it.

444
00:37:38,877 --> 00:37:43,507
Who has the perfect synthesis
of career and lifestyle?

445
00:37:44,637 --> 00:37:45,547
l give.

446
00:37:45,757 --> 00:37:47,236
Vampires!

447
00:37:47,557 --> 00:37:49,991
<i>Are you anti</i>-<i>technology</i>
<i>and anti</i>-<i>science?</i>

448
00:37:50,237 --> 00:37:51,829
<i>No, not at all.</i>

449
00:37:52,157 --> 00:37:54,876
<i>The question that</i>
<i>I'm asking is this:</i>

450
00:37:55,557 --> 00:37:56,956
<i>Are we happier...</i>

451
00:37:57,597 --> 00:38:00,953
<i>...as a human race? Is the world</i>
<i>fundamentally a better place...</i>

452
00:38:01,117 --> 00:38:03,028
<i>...because of science</i>
<i>and technology?</i>

453
00:38:03,677 --> 00:38:06,066
<i>We shop at home,</i>
<i>we surf the Web...</i>

454
00:38:06,237 --> 00:38:08,797
<i>...but at the same time</i>
<i>we feel emptier...</i>

455
00:38:10,117 --> 00:38:11,835
<i>...and more</i>
<i>cut off from each other...</i>

456
00:38:11,997 --> 00:38:13,715
<i>...than at any other time</i>
<i>in human history.</i>

457
00:38:13,917 --> 00:38:16,351
<i>We're becoming</i>
<i>a synthesized society...</i>

458
00:38:16,677 --> 00:38:18,713
<i>...in a hurry to get to the...</i>

459
00:38:32,797 --> 00:38:34,435
<i>We're looking for the meaning.</i>

460
00:38:34,717 --> 00:38:35,991
<i>What is the meaning?</i>

461
00:38:36,157 --> 00:38:38,796
<i>We have mindless jobs,</i>
<i>take frantic vacations.</i>

462
00:38:39,197 --> 00:38:42,075
<i>Deficit finance trips</i>
<i>to the mall to buy things...</i>

463
00:38:42,237 --> 00:38:45,673
<i>...that we think will fill</i>
<i>these holes in our lives.</i>

464
00:38:46,077 --> 00:38:48,466
<i>Any wonder we've lost</i>
<i>our sense of direction?</i>

465
00:39:27,637 --> 00:39:29,195
Holy shit!

466
00:39:46,757 --> 00:39:47,667
Right ascension...

467
00:39:47,917 --> 00:39:51,626
...18 hours, 36 minutes,
56.2 seconds!

468
00:39:52,717 --> 00:39:54,275
Declination...

469
00:39:54,597 --> 00:39:57,475
... + 36 degrees, 46 minutes...

470
00:39:57,797 --> 00:39:59,867
<i>...56.2 seconds!</i>

471
00:40:02,317 --> 00:40:03,670
<i>Confirm!</i>

472
00:40:03,877 --> 00:40:06,869
Right ascension,
18 hours, 36 minutes...

473
00:40:07,077 --> 00:40:09,113
...56.2 seconds!

474
00:40:09,717 --> 00:40:12,470
<i>Is anybody awake in there?</i>
<i>I'm moving the array!</i>

475
00:40:12,637 --> 00:40:14,548
<i>Confirm!</i>

476
00:40:14,797 --> 00:40:16,150
Boss has a bogey!

477
00:40:16,357 --> 00:40:18,587
<i>Right ascension, 18 hours...</i>

478
00:40:22,757 --> 00:40:23,951
We're on it!

479
00:40:24,157 --> 00:40:25,112
<i>36 hours...</i>

480
00:40:25,477 --> 00:40:27,354
<i>...47 minutes and 1 second!</i>

481
00:40:27,837 --> 00:40:29,111
<i>Strong possible...</i>

482
00:40:29,277 --> 00:40:31,666
...pulse chain on sub-array four!

483
00:40:31,877 --> 00:40:34,311
l'm moving the rest.
Confirm coordinates!

484
00:40:35,237 --> 00:40:36,989
Check the status of the array.

485
00:40:37,277 --> 00:40:38,596
She's doing all the dishes.

486
00:40:39,037 --> 00:40:39,867
Systems nominal.

487
00:40:45,517 --> 00:40:46,586
Hello.

488
00:40:47,757 --> 00:40:48,792
Full systems check!

489
00:40:49,597 --> 00:40:52,236
<i>Coordinates confirmed.</i>
<i>Willie's checking the system.</i>

490
00:40:52,477 --> 00:40:55,196
Stay on top of
the systems diagnostics!

491
00:40:55,477 --> 00:40:57,115
Check reference point offsets.

492
00:40:57,317 --> 00:41:01,151
And l want you off-axis
on 27 the second we get there!

493
00:41:01,317 --> 00:41:03,751
And tell Willie
to break out the big boy!

494
00:41:05,277 --> 00:41:06,266
Copy that.

495
00:41:07,677 --> 00:41:08,905
Yeah! Go, Ellie!

496
00:41:09,117 --> 00:41:12,154
l hear it on the headphones.
We got to be sure about this.

497
00:41:12,477 --> 00:41:14,547
Give me another array status.

498
00:41:16,317 --> 00:41:19,673
Her four are online,
the rest are tracking in.

499
00:41:22,077 --> 00:41:24,307
But there's a bad drive on 16.

500
00:41:24,517 --> 00:41:26,872
The four are online,
the rest are tracking in.

501
00:41:27,117 --> 00:41:29,790
<i>There's a bad drive on 16.</i>
<i>Copy that?</i>

502
00:41:31,197 --> 00:41:33,108
<i>What shall I do</i>
<i>about the source queue?</i>

503
00:41:33,317 --> 00:41:35,194
Forget it and hold the queue.

504
00:41:35,517 --> 00:41:39,510
Get ready to set the target frequency
to manual the second we're aligned.

505
00:41:39,717 --> 00:41:43,949
Do you copy? l want you to go
off-axis on 27 the second we're there!

506
00:41:44,157 --> 00:41:46,717
And leave the LO frequency
where it is!

507
00:41:47,037 --> 00:41:50,029
Don't let it get away!
lf you lose it, scan the band!

508
00:41:50,237 --> 00:41:52,797
Run every frequency
you can think of.

509
00:41:57,917 --> 00:41:59,191
How you doing?

510
00:42:03,557 --> 00:42:04,626
Talk to me, guys.

511
00:42:04,837 --> 00:42:08,352
Partially polarized moving pulses,
amplitude modulated.

512
00:42:08,557 --> 00:42:12,072
We're locked. Systems are fine.
What's the frequency?

513
00:42:12,317 --> 00:42:13,272
4.46...

514
00:42:13,477 --> 00:42:14,910
...23 gigahertz.

515
00:42:16,677 --> 00:42:18,235
Hydrogen times pi.

516
00:42:18,597 --> 00:42:19,666
Told you!

517
00:42:19,917 --> 00:42:21,555
Strong sucker too!

518
00:42:22,557 --> 00:42:24,036
l got it!
l'm patched in!

519
00:42:24,717 --> 00:42:25,752
Let me hear.

520
00:42:31,197 --> 00:42:32,516
Listen to that.

521
00:42:34,717 --> 00:42:36,594
Make me a liar, Fish.

522
00:42:37,037 --> 00:42:39,710
lt could be AWACS
out of Kirkland jamming us.

523
00:42:39,877 --> 00:42:40,992
But l doubt it.

524
00:42:41,237 --> 00:42:43,307
See if F.U.D.D.'s reading it too.

525
00:42:45,317 --> 00:42:47,353
Patch it back
and give me the off-axis.

526
00:42:47,917 --> 00:42:49,509
-We recording?
-Never stopped.

527
00:42:51,517 --> 00:42:52,745
Thank you, Elmer!

528
00:42:52,957 --> 00:42:54,709
AWACS status is negative.

529
00:42:54,877 --> 00:42:55,832
White Sands?

530
00:42:56,077 --> 00:42:57,590
On this frequency? No.

531
00:42:58,077 --> 00:42:59,305
l'll punch up the darks.

532
00:43:02,397 --> 00:43:03,512
How's spying tonight?

533
00:43:04,597 --> 00:43:05,825
Come on!

534
00:43:08,077 --> 00:43:10,432
NORAD's not tracking
any snoops in this vector.

535
00:43:10,837 --> 00:43:12,156
Shuttle's in sleep mode.

536
00:43:12,477 --> 00:43:14,547
Okay, point source confirmed.

537
00:43:14,837 --> 00:43:16,350
Whatever it is, it ain't local.

538
00:43:16,557 --> 00:43:17,353
Position?

539
00:43:17,557 --> 00:43:19,946
l checked interferometry.
Somewhere in Lyra.

540
00:43:20,157 --> 00:43:21,715
-Vega?
-Can't be!

541
00:43:21,957 --> 00:43:23,868
lt's only 26 light years away.

542
00:43:24,077 --> 00:43:25,908
-Peak intensity?
-Coming up!

543
00:43:27,157 --> 00:43:27,828
Vega.

544
00:43:28,597 --> 00:43:32,306
Vega. l scanned it a bunch of times
at Arecibo. lt was always negative.

545
00:43:32,517 --> 00:43:33,427
Got it!

546
00:43:33,597 --> 00:43:35,394
Reading over 100 janskys.

547
00:43:36,077 --> 00:43:38,466
Jesus! l can pick it up on my...

548
00:43:41,277 --> 00:43:42,232
No!

549
00:44:14,157 --> 00:44:15,112
Come on!

550
00:44:17,277 --> 00:44:18,392
lt's restarting.

551
00:44:19,797 --> 00:44:21,469
Wait a minute.
Those are numbers.

552
00:44:21,637 --> 00:44:23,355
That was 3, before it was 2.

553
00:44:24,757 --> 00:44:27,225
Base 10 numbers.
Count and see how far we get.

554
00:44:28,277 --> 00:44:28,789
One.

555
00:44:35,197 --> 00:44:36,152
Seven.

556
00:44:38,877 --> 00:44:40,356
Those are primes.

557
00:44:40,597 --> 00:44:43,634
2, 3, 5, 7 are all prime numbers.

558
00:44:44,077 --> 00:44:45,874
No way that's a natural phenomenon!

559
00:44:46,077 --> 00:44:48,796
Let's just calm down
and pull up the star file on Vega.

560
00:44:50,237 --> 00:44:53,388
lt doesn't make any sense.
The system is too young.

561
00:44:53,597 --> 00:44:55,189
lt can't have a planetary system...

562
00:44:55,357 --> 00:44:58,474
...let alone life
or a technological civilization.

563
00:44:58,717 --> 00:45:01,072
Maybe they're not from there,
they're visiting.

564
00:45:01,277 --> 00:45:04,474
Spacecraft? This system's full
of debris. lt'd get clobbered.

565
00:45:04,877 --> 00:45:08,790
Not if they used their
laser blasters and photon torpedoes.

566
00:45:09,037 --> 00:45:11,835
-That's not funny.
-How else can we explain it!

567
00:45:12,357 --> 00:45:15,190
He's right. lf we go public
with this and we're wrong...

568
00:45:15,357 --> 00:45:17,507
...it's over. We're cooked.

569
00:45:20,237 --> 00:45:21,556
l wish Kent was here.

570
00:45:21,757 --> 00:45:25,033
Whatever it is, let's do something.
Vega will set.

571
00:45:28,317 --> 00:45:32,469
<i>Position confirmed. We've got 4.4623</i>
<i>gigahertz, confirmed.</i>

572
00:45:32,637 --> 00:45:35,390
<i>We've got 112 janskys.</i>

573
00:45:35,677 --> 00:45:37,793
Do you have a source location yet?

574
00:45:40,277 --> 00:45:42,552
<i>We put it right smack in the middle.</i>

575
00:45:43,197 --> 00:45:44,391
<i>Vega.</i>

576
00:45:46,477 --> 00:45:49,275
Thanks. Keep tracking
and we'll get back to you.

577
00:45:49,517 --> 00:45:50,745
<i>Right</i>-<i>o.</i>

578
00:46:01,597 --> 00:46:03,269
101 . The pulse sequenced...

579
00:46:03,437 --> 00:46:06,713
...through every prime number
between 2 and 101 .

580
00:46:08,557 --> 00:46:10,149
Who do we call now?

581
00:46:13,277 --> 00:46:14,232
Everybody.

582
00:46:21,677 --> 00:46:25,067
<i>The rumors are flying,</i>
<i>the implications extraordinary.</i>

583
00:46:25,277 --> 00:46:27,029
<i>Detection of an unidentified...</i>

584
00:46:27,277 --> 00:46:31,316
<i>...radio source from space</i>
<i>can neither be confirmed nor denied.</i>

585
00:46:31,557 --> 00:46:33,354
<i>But the military arriving...</i>

586
00:46:33,557 --> 00:46:36,993
Sources close to the VLA
report they have been contacted...

587
00:46:37,197 --> 00:46:39,108
...by some form
of intelligent being...

588
00:46:39,317 --> 00:46:43,674
...living outside our solar system.
Again, there is no confirmation.

589
00:46:46,677 --> 00:46:48,668
l want all of these people
out of here.

590
00:46:49,477 --> 00:46:50,751
Where's the girl?

591
00:46:55,197 --> 00:46:56,471
<i>22 stations worldwide...</i>

592
00:46:56,677 --> 00:46:58,030
...now confirm the signal.

593
00:46:58,197 --> 00:46:59,789
Vega's now below our horizon.

594
00:46:59,997 --> 00:47:02,227
You're hearing the signal
from the Russian...

595
00:47:02,437 --> 00:47:03,995
Get decryption people here.

596
00:47:04,197 --> 00:47:06,153
Lunacharsky's visiting at Cal Tech.

597
00:47:06,357 --> 00:47:07,676
Explain this to me.

598
00:47:07,877 --> 00:47:11,756
lf the source of the signal is so
sophisticated...why the remedial math?

599
00:47:11,957 --> 00:47:13,310
Why not just speak English?

600
00:47:13,477 --> 00:47:16,753
Maybe because 70%of the planet
speaks other languages.

601
00:47:16,917 --> 00:47:19,636
Mathematics is the
only truly universal language.

602
00:47:20,277 --> 00:47:22,711
lt's no coincidence
that they're using primes.

603
00:47:22,957 --> 00:47:23,833
l don't get it.

604
00:47:24,117 --> 00:47:25,266
Prime numbers.

605
00:47:25,477 --> 00:47:28,833
lntegers only divisible
by themselves and 1 .

606
00:47:31,677 --> 00:47:34,396
We think this may be a beacon,
an announcement...

607
00:47:34,677 --> 00:47:36,349
...to get our attention.

608
00:47:36,517 --> 00:47:40,112
lf it's attention you want,
you got that. One thing: Vega.

609
00:47:40,317 --> 00:47:43,627
People have looked at Vega
for years, with no results.

610
00:47:43,797 --> 00:47:46,630
Yesterday they start
broadcasting primes. Why?

611
00:47:46,877 --> 00:47:48,151
lt's hardly yesterday.

612
00:47:48,357 --> 00:47:50,871
The signal's been transmitting
for 26 years.

613
00:47:52,117 --> 00:47:53,550
Excuse me, who are you?

614
00:47:53,757 --> 00:47:56,066
Michael Kitz,
National Security Advisor.

615
00:47:56,277 --> 00:47:57,551
Your reputation...

616
00:47:57,717 --> 00:48:00,993
First, ask the gentlemen
with the guns to wait outside.

617
00:48:01,637 --> 00:48:03,628
This is a civilian facility.

618
00:48:09,917 --> 00:48:11,270
With all due respect...

619
00:48:11,477 --> 00:48:12,307
Excuse me.

620
00:48:13,757 --> 00:48:15,873
Hi! l'm so glad you're back!

621
00:48:16,437 --> 00:48:17,586
Come hear this.

622
00:48:18,277 --> 00:48:19,551
ls this great?

623
00:48:19,717 --> 00:48:21,992
-Who are all these people?
-l have no idea.

624
00:48:22,197 --> 00:48:25,234
Sit down. We need help
with the spectrum analysis.

625
00:48:25,437 --> 00:48:26,950
-l'll get on it.
-Headsets.

626
00:48:27,197 --> 00:48:29,267
l'll just come right to the point.

627
00:48:29,477 --> 00:48:33,311
Announcing this all over the world may
well be a breach of national security.

628
00:48:33,477 --> 00:48:35,115
lt's not a person-to-person call.

629
00:48:35,317 --> 00:48:39,276
You think a civilization sending this
message intends it just for Americans?

630
00:48:39,477 --> 00:48:41,229
You might have consulted us.

631
00:48:41,597 --> 00:48:45,431
-The contents could be very sensitive.
-You want to classify prime numbers?

632
00:48:46,037 --> 00:48:49,234
Due to earth's rotation, we're
in line with Vega only hours a day.

633
00:48:49,437 --> 00:48:53,589
The only way to monitor the signal
is to cooperate with other stations.

634
00:48:53,797 --> 00:48:57,949
lf Dr. Arroway hadn't acted quickly,
we'd have lost key elements.

635
00:48:58,117 --> 00:48:59,596
Fine, they've got the primes.

636
00:48:59,837 --> 00:49:02,476
But if a more significant
transmission is to come...

637
00:49:02,717 --> 00:49:04,594
We need help to receive and decode.

638
00:49:04,797 --> 00:49:07,311
You understand
that my job is to protect...

639
00:49:08,557 --> 00:49:10,388
-Listen.
-l hear it.

640
00:49:10,677 --> 00:49:11,587
Hear what?

641
00:49:11,797 --> 00:49:12,707
Harmonic.

642
00:49:12,917 --> 00:49:16,592
Bingo! l had Willie ask Rattan
to retune to 8.9247 gigahertz.

643
00:49:16,757 --> 00:49:18,315
There's a lot more here.

644
00:49:18,517 --> 00:49:21,077
-Get on the negative sideband.
-l'm already on it.

645
00:49:21,237 --> 00:49:22,306
What is it?

646
00:49:22,517 --> 00:49:23,950
Another signal!

647
00:49:24,117 --> 00:49:26,870
A second signal at double
the frequency. Looks like...

648
00:49:27,677 --> 00:49:28,951
Get a TV monitor!

649
00:49:29,677 --> 00:49:31,474
Patch it into the image processor.

650
00:49:31,677 --> 00:49:32,871
Want the new data?

651
00:49:33,077 --> 00:49:34,795
Yeah, the new one we just recorded.

652
00:49:34,997 --> 00:49:36,874
David, explain this to me, please.

653
00:49:37,077 --> 00:49:39,750
There's another signal.
Looks like a TV transmission.

654
00:49:39,957 --> 00:49:40,867
We're hot.

655
00:49:41,117 --> 00:49:43,711
Go get the blinds.
There is a lot of glare.

656
00:49:44,757 --> 00:49:46,110
You're patched in.

657
00:49:46,357 --> 00:49:49,633
lt's definitely an image.
Let's try and stabilize it.

658
00:49:54,197 --> 00:49:55,835
What do you make of that?

659
00:49:56,037 --> 00:49:58,915
lt's two different
interlaced frames. l'm framing one.

660
00:50:02,117 --> 00:50:04,756
-lt's just noise.
-Trying frame two.

661
00:50:05,917 --> 00:50:09,114
l've got an offset carrier.
l think it's audio.

662
00:50:09,317 --> 00:50:10,511
Plug it in!

663
00:50:14,677 --> 00:50:15,871
Center that segment.

664
00:50:16,077 --> 00:50:17,146
Centering.

665
00:50:21,237 --> 00:50:22,511
Can you clean it up?

666
00:50:22,677 --> 00:50:24,110
l'm working on it.

667
00:50:36,517 --> 00:50:37,916
What the hell...?

668
00:50:38,597 --> 00:50:39,825
Try zooming out.

669
00:50:43,677 --> 00:50:44,587
Freeze!

670
00:50:44,757 --> 00:50:45,985
Reverse values.

671
00:50:47,557 --> 00:50:49,275
Try zooming out again.

672
00:50:53,117 --> 00:50:55,187
Rotate 90 degrees counterclock...

673
00:50:56,677 --> 00:50:58,190
My God!

674
00:51:04,637 --> 00:51:06,036
What's going on?

675
00:51:06,557 --> 00:51:08,832
You're not going to believe this.

676
00:51:21,717 --> 00:51:23,389
Does anybody speak German?

677
00:51:24,797 --> 00:51:27,072
"l declare the Games in Berlin...

678
00:51:28,117 --> 00:51:29,755
...at the celebration...

679
00:51:29,957 --> 00:51:32,710
...of the first Olympics
of the New Era...

680
00:51:32,917 --> 00:51:34,191
...as opened."

681
00:51:44,517 --> 00:51:45,916
Get me the White House.

682
00:51:46,677 --> 00:51:48,986
20 million people died
defeating the bastard...

683
00:51:49,197 --> 00:51:51,870
...and he's our first ambassador
to outer space?

684
00:51:52,077 --> 00:51:55,228
The broadcast of the '36 Olympics
was the first TV transmission...

685
00:51:55,477 --> 00:51:56,910
...that went into space.

686
00:51:57,117 --> 00:52:00,348
Sending it back is a way of saying,
"Hello, we heard you."

687
00:52:00,517 --> 00:52:02,712
Or, <i>"Sieg Heil,</i>
you're our kind of people."

688
00:52:02,917 --> 00:52:05,306
Hitler's politics
have nothing to do with this.

689
00:52:05,517 --> 00:52:09,032
lt's unlikely they understood it.
People must understand...

690
00:52:09,197 --> 00:52:11,427
The people are
in very good hands, Doctor.

691
00:52:11,637 --> 00:52:13,309
We'll take it from here.

692
00:52:14,317 --> 00:52:16,228
Smile, folks. We're on.

693
00:52:16,517 --> 00:52:18,712
<i>A message of unknown origin</i>
<i>from deep space...</i>

694
00:52:18,917 --> 00:52:22,432
<i>... was received by American</i>
<i>scientists. Now to the White House.</i>

695
00:52:22,877 --> 00:52:25,949
<i>We're told the President</i>
<i>will have only a few remarks...</i>

696
00:52:26,237 --> 00:52:27,636
<i>...about today's</i>
<i>extraordinary events...</i>

697
00:52:27,837 --> 00:52:31,068
<i>...and that he won't be taking</i>
<i>any questions from the press.</i>

698
00:52:35,837 --> 00:52:37,065
<i>Good afternoon.</i>

699
00:52:39,837 --> 00:52:41,907
<i>I'm glad to be joined by my...</i>

700
00:52:42,077 --> 00:52:43,908
<i>...Science and Technology Advisor.</i>

701
00:52:45,597 --> 00:52:48,350
<i>This is the product</i>
<i>of years of exploration...</i>

702
00:52:48,517 --> 00:52:51,634
<i>...by some of the world's</i>
<i>most distinguished scientists.</i>

703
00:52:51,837 --> 00:52:53,429
<i>Like all discoveries...</i>

704
00:52:53,597 --> 00:52:55,827
<i>...this one will continue</i>
<i>to be reviewed...</i>

705
00:52:56,077 --> 00:52:57,066
<i>...examined...</i>

706
00:52:57,237 --> 00:52:58,716
<i>...and scrutinized.</i>

707
00:52:58,917 --> 00:53:01,795
<i>It must be confirmed</i>
<i>by other scientists.</i>

708
00:53:02,037 --> 00:53:03,152
<i>But clearly...</i>

709
00:53:03,717 --> 00:53:07,027
<i>...the fact that this is being</i>
<i>explored is a vindication...</i>

710
00:53:07,837 --> 00:53:11,512
Fish, what is the story over here?
l thought Ellie was supposed to be on.

711
00:53:11,677 --> 00:53:13,110
l don't know.

712
00:53:13,717 --> 00:53:14,991
Guys?

713
00:53:17,277 --> 00:53:19,837
Those interlaced frames
we thought were noise?

714
00:53:20,797 --> 00:53:23,357
This has structure.
l'm hearing structure.

715
00:53:24,637 --> 00:53:26,867
<i>If this discovery is confirmed...</i>

716
00:53:27,037 --> 00:53:30,552
<i>...it will be one of the most stunning</i>
<i>insights into our universe...</i>

717
00:53:30,717 --> 00:53:32,673
<i>...that science has ever uncovered.</i>

718
00:53:33,157 --> 00:53:35,432
<i>Its implications</i>
<i>are as far</i>-<i>reaching...</i>

719
00:53:35,637 --> 00:53:38,105
<i>...and awe</i>-<i>inspiring</i>
<i>as can be imagined.</i>

720
00:53:38,397 --> 00:53:41,628
<i>Even as it promises answers</i>
<i>to some of our oldest questions...</i>

721
00:53:41,877 --> 00:53:43,356
<i>...it poses still others...</i>

722
00:53:43,557 --> 00:53:45,115
<i>...even more fundamental.</i>

723
00:53:45,317 --> 00:53:47,148
<i>We will continue</i>
<i>to listen closely...</i>

724
00:53:47,357 --> 00:53:48,836
<i>...to what it has to say...</i>

725
00:53:48,997 --> 00:53:51,033
<i>...as we continue</i>
<i>the search for answers...</i>

726
00:53:51,237 --> 00:53:52,431
<i>...and for knowledge...</i>

727
00:53:52,677 --> 00:53:54,872
<i>...that is as old</i>
<i>as humanity itself...</i>

728
00:53:55,077 --> 00:53:57,875
<i>...but essential</i>
<i>to our people's future.</i>

729
00:53:58,277 --> 00:53:58,948
<i>Thank you.</i>

730
00:53:59,157 --> 00:54:01,910
ls there a renewed assessment
of security threat?

731
00:54:02,197 --> 00:54:05,109
<i>I'll answer your questions</i>
<i>after a few corrections.</i>

732
00:54:05,277 --> 00:54:06,915
<i>The message was received Friday...</i>

733
00:54:07,157 --> 00:54:09,113
<i>...at 6:31 a.m.</i>
<i>Mountain Standard Time.</i>

734
00:54:09,317 --> 00:54:10,875
<i>It was largely mathematical...</i>

735
00:54:11,037 --> 00:54:13,631
<i>...and in spite of reports</i>
<i>to the contrary...</i>

736
00:54:13,917 --> 00:54:16,306
<i>...appears to be</i>
<i>completely benign in nature.</i>

737
00:54:16,517 --> 00:54:20,305
<i>Let me say that again.</i>
<i>The message is completely benign.</i>

738
00:54:20,517 --> 00:54:23,509
<i>The President has contacted</i>
<i>the world's heads of state...</i>

739
00:54:23,717 --> 00:54:26,390
<i>...and every security measure</i>
<i>is being taken.</i>

740
00:54:26,597 --> 00:54:29,555
